{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d5a800b1-2394-4690-87c0-967aee529a4d","content":"Here's my assessment of the template:\n\n**✅ Required fields present:** `identity`, `name`, `shortName`, `author`, `tags`, `sourceName`\n\n**⚠️ Issues to fix before publishing:**\n\n1. **Missing `$schema`** — Add `\"$schema\": \"http://json.schemastore.org/template\"` for validation support.\n2. **Missing `groupIdentity`** — Needed for NuGet so templates are grouped properly (e.g., `\"groupIdentity\": \"MyCompany.WebApi\"`).\n3. **`Framework` symbol has no `replaces`** — The chosen framework value won't actually be substituted in your project files. You likely need `\"replaces\": \"net9.0\"` (or a matching token) so the target framework gets swapped.\n4. **Missing `preferNameDirectory`** — Recommended as `true` for project-type templates.\n5. **Missing `defaultName`** — Without it, `dotnet new` will generate a default name like `Template` instead of something meaningful.\n\n**Verdict:** Not quite ready. The `Framework` symbol is effectively a no-op without `replaces`, which is a functional bug. The other items are best-practice gaps that matter for a polished NuGet package.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bdd663e6-5cc5-4234-806c-bc966c12b5e1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Let me review this template.json for NuGet publishing readiness. I'll check against the .NET template engine schema requirements.\n\nIssues I can see:\n\n1. **Missing `$schema`** — Best practice to include `\"$schema\": \"http://json.schemastore.org/template\"` for validation.\n2. **Missing `groupIdentity`** — Recommended for NuGet packaging so templates can be grouped.\n3. **Missing `precedence`** — Useful when multiple versions of a template exist.\n4. **Missing `preferNameDirectory`** — Common for project templates.\n5. **The `defaultValue` for Framework is `net9.0`** — but the `sourceName` replacement and `Framework` symbol don't have a `replaces` property, so the chosen framework value won't actually be substituted anywhere.\n\n\n6. **The `Framework` symbol is missing a `replaces` property** — this means the framework selection won't actually modify any files in the generated template.\n\nThe core required fields are all present (`identity`, `name`, `shortName`, `author`), but several recommended properties like `$schema`, `groupIdentity`, and `preferNameDirectory` would improve the template's robustness for NuGet distribution.\n\nI'm also noticing `defaultName` is missing, which would provide a sensible default project name when users don't specify one. Let me check what other files are in the working directory to get more context about the template structure.","outputTokens":696},"id":"1991a1b9-99de-4df9-9296-fa55f5d21cef","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:41:07.975Z","parentId":"1bd751e2-3ed2-41c9-ad40-f204969d3032"}
